<New PAsource="" >A FORMER anti-drugs campaigner </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >was jailed for </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >seven </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >years - </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >for </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >dealing in </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >heroin.</Verbatim>


<New PAsource="" >For four years </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >David Francis, 37, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >counselled addicts as team leader of a Home Office-funded drug awareness drive.</New>


<New PAsource="" >During that time he had high-level meetings with police and gave evidence to a Commons committee. </New>
<New PAsource="" >But after quitting the job, he cynically supplied the people he had been recruited to help.</New>


<Verbatim PAsource="" >Francis, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >who used boys as young as 12 as couriers, was caught with </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >heroin </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >worth £72,000 </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >after </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >months of surveillance. </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >He admitted at </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Nottingham Crown Court </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >possessing </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >heroin. </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >Two of his lieutenants were given jail terms totalling </Rewrite>
<New PAsource="" >10 </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >and a half years.</Verbatim>


<New PAsource="" >Jailing </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Francis, Judge Dudley Bennett </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >said "You more than anybody else should have known the misery of people who had become addicted."</New>



